{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_damask_ver02/data/sn89065008/00199916609/1920092201/1170.xml":{"full_text":"y\n\nthe commonwealth.\ndaily\nReliable Loca l Newpaper\nWEEKLY EDITION\nWEEKLY\nL. cY S. Gillespi e, Editors and Publisi\nSubscription, $i.r\u00bbo YEAR\ns i-r s\nVOL. 24-NO. 46\nGREENWOOD, LEFLORE COUNTY,\nMISSISSIPPI. WEDNESDAY, SEPT. 22. 1920\nCONTRIBUTIONS\nOF DEMOCRATS\nNOT LIMITED\nAs Far As Individuals\nAre Concerned, Says\nGerard.\nSAYS 2 MILLION\nBE SUFFICIENT\nGives Names Of Com\nmittee To Investi\ngators.\nAssociated Press\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 22 The\nI Democratic National Finance Com\nI mittee is not limiting the size of cam\npaign contributions from single indi\nI viduals but two million dollars total\nwill be sufficient for the Democra\ntic National Campaign, James W. Ge\nrard, chairman of the Committee tes\ntified today before the Senate Cam\npaign Investigation Committee. Ge\nIrrd gave the names of the men and\nwomen he asked to serve on the com\nmittee and declared he was endeavor\ning to form a local committee for\neach State. He said he had raised\n$128,000 so far\nCHIEF OF FIRE\nDEPT. RESIGNS\nMr. Leon Bridges Files Resignation\nAt Council Meeting\u2014Other\nBusiness Transacted.\nAt a regular meeting of the City\nCouncil last night, the resignation\nof Mr. Leon Bridges as fire chief,\nwas filed and the same accepted by\nthe Council. It will take effect on\nOctober 1st.\ncepted a position with the Louisiana\nOil Refining Co., of Shreveport,\nMr. Bridges has ac\nLa.\nI For the past three years Mr. Brid\nIges has been fire chief in Green\nIwood. The Council appointed Mr. J.\nI B. Caldwell,\n(chief, to fill the vacancy made by\nI the resignation of Mr. Bridges. Mr.\n(Caldwell has been in the service of\nI the Greenwood Fire Department for\nI the past two years.\nI Mr. L. A. Williams, public account\nlant, was awarded the contract to au\nI dit the city books for the fiscal year,\n[ending October 1st. at a stipulated\n[price of $250.\nThe Council rejected bids received\nfrom two pump concerns to supply a\npump for Greenwood, to take care of\nthe flooded streets after heavy rains\n[in the city. Bids wil again be re\nceived. The rejection of the bids\n[submitted was due to fact that de\nlivery could not be made before sev\nen months and the city is anxious to\ninstall the pump before the heavy\nspring rains.\nMayor E. V. Hughston was author\nized to borrow $15,000 for school pur\nposes to tide the city over until the\nthe revenue begins to come into the\ntreasury.\nwho is assistant fire\n[Profiteers Being\nFlogged In Budapest\nAssociated Press\nI BUDAPEST, Sept. 22\u2014Flogging as\n[a punishment for convicted profiteers\n[has proved so satisfactory to the pub\n[lic that the Ministry of Justice is\nconsidering its infliction for other\n[offenses.\nRotary Club Holds\nIts Weekly Luneheon\nThe Rotary Club held its weekly\nluncheon yesterday at 1 o'clock at the\nReiman House. About 27 members\nWe re present. The guests of the club\nWere M r w. H. Radabaugh of Mo\nbile, Ala., Mr. O'Sullivan of New Or\nleans and Mr. James Carnes of\nGreenwood. Interesting talks were\nmade by three guests.\n\nCotton Editor C. A\nWas Hpro Tndav\nWdS nere louaj\n\nMr. George L. Fossick, the able cot\nton market editor of the Memphis\nGommercial Appeal, spent today in\nGreenwood and made The Daily Com\nmonwealth a pleasant call. Mr. Fos- j\n8ick >s making an inspection tour of\nike Delta this week and reports the\ncotton crop as having very much de- i\nteriorated at all points visited.\n-_o_\nTaka The Daily Commonwealth, i\nCOW PUNCHER\nIS CONDUCTING\nRESCUE MISSION\nFEEDS HUNGRY CHILDREN AND\nTIRED SOULS ARE COMFORT\nED IN BUENOS AIRES.\nAssociated Press\nBUENOS AIRES, Sept. 22-On a\nstreet in Buenos Aires which might\nbe called the backwash of the world\njudging from the human derelicts\ncast up from every stream and every\nland, a North American cow puncher\nof the old West is conducting\ncue mission whore hungry children\nare fed and tired souls are comfort\ned. He is John Calvert de Bohun,\nwho says he \"was bom on the hurri\ncane deck of a cayuse\" in New Mexi\na res\nco.\nCowboy, jockey, wanderer ,and fin\nally ordained minister, Bohun's life\nhas been such as to make him one\nwith the dead wood that drifts into\nhis mission, as he tells his story, and\nhis redemption to bodily and spirit\nual health a parallel to that of some\nof his people. There was a time, he\nsays, when American whiskey was no\nlonger strong enough for him so that\nhe satisfied his appetite with Chin\nese whiskey, which is like drinking\nmixed turpentine and banana oil.\nBut through the years came glim\npses to him of something better. A\ntouch of remorse in Australia, a good\nexample in Europe, the sight of a\nwoman who reminded him of one he\n\"used to know\", the influence of\nFather Damien, who gave his life to\nthe lepers of Hawaii and who was so\nloved that there was scarcely a di-y\neye in grog shop or ship's cabin from\nManila to Melbourne when he died,\nsuch things made him wonder. And\nfinally worn and world-knowing,\nwhen he drifted back to that New\nMexico from which he had started\nand found \"Tom the Devil\" preach\ning instead of running the old gamb\nling game ,and later saw others fol\nlow in his steps, Bohun says that the,\nlight came to him. He became a\nminister.\nBohun's mission) is located in a\nbuilding something in appearance\nlike San Antonio's Alamo, and with\na history as eventful as those who\nBuilt for a Masonic\nrepair to it.\nlodge many years ago, it has been\nvariously dance hall, gambling house,\nheadquarters of Black Hand in Ar\ngentina and is now a combination\nchurch,\nfirst aid to the morally injured.\nIn tjie room where once women and\ndrank and danced, now there are\nschool, orphan's home and\nmen\nreligious services in Spanish, and\nbetween times children, seldom less\nthan 100 of them, at lunch or supper.\nChildren of every race and religion\nfed there. Other work of the\nmission is with lepers, and with old\nThe mission of\nare\nE.\nJ.\nE.\nJ.\nmen and women,\nwhich Bohun took charge about four\nyears ago, is not maintained by any\norganization, but is held together by\nfree will subscriptions.\nWhe Bohun talks with a visitor,\nparticularly with an American who\nknows the West, his references to his\nwork are mingled with spontaneous\ntales of \"hard riding and hard shoot\nOf John Wesley Harding,\nW.\nO.\nH.\nL.\nW.\nJ.\nC.\nJ.\nB.\nS.\nE.\nG.\nDr.\ning men.\"\nfor instance, the frock-coated gamb\nler of El Paso, who, Bohun says had\nkilled 14 men, but \"was every inch a\ngentleman and always killed with re\ngret\"; of Calamity Jane, whose story\nbound up with the fight between\nlaw and things as they wre that de\nsolated Tombstone, Arizona; of Mo\nroso, king of cattle thieves; of Wild\nBill Hikok, who met his end at Dodge\nCity; and of many more who made\nMinis\nA'as\nC.\nJ.\nY.\nR.\nJ.\nthe West a place of romance,\nter though he is, he is still a cowboy,\nbent on getting his herd cafe into the\nfinal round-up.\n--o\nRecognized The\nSinn Fein Republic\nAssociated Press\nPARIS, Sept. 22\u2014The Irish Sinn\nFein republic has been \"recognized\"\nby the Mayor at Versailles but the\nrecognizer ie I* 1 danger of losing his\njob.\ncent centenary celebration.\nIthe foreigners who placed wreaths\nland delivered speeches before the\nstatute of General Hoche was an\nIt happened in the course of a re\nAmong\n\nvoy from a country wh h has been\nmeritione( quite frequently in despa\nen\n[tches lately as the \"dejure\" Irish re\npublic. The Mayor replied with great\nenthusiasm to the Sinn Feiners ora-\ntion, lauding \"the new republic\" which\nhad grown out of the\nj The British Embassy at Paris pro-\ntested to the Quai d'Orsay and the\nMayor has been asked to brush up is\ni grography and explain how it hap-\npe ns that he is unaware that Ireland\nis still a part of the friendly British\ni Empire.\n\nI\nSeptember Eve\n\nf\nfMMw'Twtt >i., *V 'if A r^rw/A 'i\n1 iSriMH\niff\nif# f\nm\n\\t\n\nii\nV\n-.Mi\nI* i\nIVil\n\n\n\nI mmk\n%\\tr~\n[Hi\nf\u00a7f\nO\n\u25a0*T\nl\nI\n\nr\nI\n[ft\nCS*\nmi\nME j\n:7j'\nr\n\n\nWm\n\n\nwm\n\nli\n\n\n1\n5\n\n\u2022/j\nm\n4.\nM\n(COVirl.Ml\n.L\nA\na\nhe\nof\nto\nso\nMONEY NEEDED\nFAD nriUAcn a rri/1\nFOR DEMOCRATIC\nCAMPAIGN FUND\nTO MEET EXPENSES IN EFFORT\nTO ELECT COX AND\nROOSEVELT.\na\na\nT\nr p0 7 1\u00b0 i n aPPC\nNational and State Democratic Exe\nwS to\u00b0\": /xpenlrteiS\nto carrying on the campaign in be\nhalf of Cox and Roosevelt, our can\ndidates for President and Vice- Pres-;\nident, The Daily Commonwealth will\nreceive voluntary subscriptions to|\nthis fund and forward same to head\nquarters to be used where they will\ndo the most good for the cause of\nDemocracy.\nThe Republicans are raising an\nenormous campaign fund from the\nbig business interests of the country,\nand it is up to the masses to contri\nbute the necessary funds with which\nto meet the actual expenses of the\nDemocratic Campaign Committee.\nAll contributions will be acknow\nledged in these columns, and we hope'\nthe responses will be liberal, prompt\ng 0 Q\nand numerous\nThe Daily Commonwealth .$10.00\nShelby S. Stele\nE. L. Mounger\nJ. Kantor\nE. H. Crippen\nJ. R. Forrester\nDr. W. T. Johnson\n6 00\n5.001\n2.00;\n25.00:\n6.00;\nnf\n1-00\n1 on\n1'0\u00ab\nW. S. Hill\nO. F. Bledsoe, Jr.\nH. Y. Fraiser\nL. S. Rogers\nCapt. P. W. Shearer\nMiss Ruth Shearer\nW. S. Wingfield\nJ. J. Barrow\nC. A. Pitchford\nCapt. S. M. Anderson\nJ. D. Lanham\nB. F. Dulweber\nS. I. Osbom\nE. V. Schilling\nG. W. Chambless\nDr. T. R. Henderson .10.00\n1.00\n1.00\n5.00\n1.00\n5.00\n5.00\n5.00\n10.00\n2.00\n2.60\n1.00\n2.00\nC. W. Telfair\nJohn T. Wells\nJ. L. Montgomery\nY. T. Eggleston\nR. Y. Wright\nJ. B. Webb\nRagsdale McNeill\nDalton McBee\nH. G. Kitchell\nB. A. Williamson\nM. F. Pierce\nGid Montjoy, Sr.\nE. E. Kersh\n25.00\n5.00\n1.00\n\n1.00 I\n1.00\n\n2.50\n1\n\n1 00\n1.00\n3.00 1\nI\nW. Morgan Kimbrough 3.00 j\nR. A. Joiner\nHarris Gray *.001\nDelta Steam Laundry 5.00\n1 00\n10.00\n1.00\nJ. E. Dennis\nS. G. Wilson\nJ. G. Pleasants\nJ. W. George\nG. A. Wilson, Jr.\nW. M. Whittington\nDr. E. W. Hunter\nDr. F. M. Sandifer\nI\ni\nI\nI\n10.00\n25.00\n5.00\n10.00\ni.oo\n$238.50 j\nTotal\nMr. James H. Caldwell, Miss Alma j\nCaldwell, Mr. Hamilton Caldwell and j\nMiss Ina Brown of Charleston, were\nvisitors in Greenwood yesterday. j\n\n\u2014o-\nMr. T. H. Gooch, a popular travel\ning salesman, is in the city today.\nCOTTON MA RKETS\nBEW Z Z'Z STfJ\nPrcv.\nOct,\n28.95 28.96 27.35127.80128.76!\nDec. 26.20 26.20 25.00j25.33j26.10j\nJan.\n24.85 24.85 23.92.24 20 24.SB\nClosed 65 to 05 down\nNew York Spots 30,50\u201450 down.\nNEW ORLEANS COTTON MARKET!\nOpen High Low Close O oso\nPrev\nj*- 1^4 25 24 26 j 23 10 2T 52 24 isi\n[i 4 ^i' 2 \u00ae;?L 1 0| 2 :L 52 24 18\nClosed 66 to 100 down.\nNew Orleans Spots 28.00.\nto|\nj****#***\u00bb**#*#|\nj\nTHE WEATHER\n\n\n\nMISSISSIPPI\u2014Rain tonight, Thurs\nday rain in the North portion. Fair\nin the South portion. Southern winds\ndiminishing tonight.\nObservations.\nTEMPERATURE\u2014Highest, 91 de\ngres; lowest, 63 degrees; precipita\ntion, trace; river gauge 6.6; fall in 24\nhours 0.3.\nj-u\nISjThe Rhode Royal\nCircus Is Coining\n\nMiss Annie Long Stephen\nLocal Observer.\nj\n\nxhe advent of the Rhoda Royal's\ngreatest shows, on Tuesday Oct. 6,\n\nwill, it is said, mark an epoch in the\n\nmatter of tented amusements. That\n\ncomplete one, containing the finest\n\ncollection of rare wild beasts ever on\n\nthe coast. The newspapers all along\n\nthe line speak highly of this huge en\n,1\ntertamment, and the \"small boy,\n\nwell as those older folks who will\n\n\nj\n\n\nthis show will present the finest\nstreet, pageant Greenwood has yet\nwitnessed, is asserted without qual\nification. That the circus company\nnumbers more circus performers than\nhas heretofore been gathered together\nunder any one management, is also\nstated positively. Thousands of dol\nlars cash were expended last winter\nin accumulating new features.\nThe menagerie is said to be a very\n\nI\nbe delighted again with the feats of!\nU(, e many ma le and female perform-j\n\u00ae\u00ae|ers, the handsome horses, the wonder\nful exhibition of wild beasts in the\ncircular steel cage, the marvelous\naerial acts, and the exciting races on\nthe hippodrome track.\nThe lack of \"sure thing\" men and\nf a (ers a so a j^ s materially to the en\njoyment of the spectator.\nThe reputation of Rhoda Royal for;\nf a j t |,f u ]]y carrying out all his advance\npromises and for dealing fairly with\nthe public in all things, affords pos\nitive assurance that his show will\n[eclipse anything of a like nature seen\nhere before.\n-o\nSmall Fire At The\nA. Weiler Residence\nT$ic fire department was called to\nthe home of Mr. and Mrs. A. Weiler\non Market Street last night. The\nc,tove wood pile and the coal house\ni n theiback yard had caught on fire.:\nThe department extinguished the\nblaze and the damage will not exceed\n$20. j\nBREEDERS FINE\n_ II711\nLIVE STOCK AND\nHOGS THIS STATE\n\nWILL COMPETE WITH THU OTH\nER STATES AT THE TRI\nSTATE FAIR.\nMEMPHIS, Tenn., Sept. 22-(Spc\ncial)-Breeders of fine live stock and\n5 th ir\nf tl finest stock in Americ a at the\nTri-State Fair in Memphis this year,\nNo less than 13 states are represen\nted in the cattle department and\nmany in the hog depaitmem.\ni\u201ecl u rio many that have been showing\n*j at the greatest fairs in the United\nStates this year. The Memphis show\nwill be the biggest in the history of\nthe Tri-State Fair. There is a pre\nmium list in the livestock department,\nalone of more than $31,000.\nThe Enochs Farms of Femwood,\nMiss., will have a string of 12 head\nof Herefords in the competition. As\nj an indication of the keen interest,\nsome\nas\nMorns\ni more than 135 head of Herefords will\nj he shown fro ma half dozen states.\nj While late entries always are\nex\nj pected, no Mississippi breeder had\nentered Shorthorns, Angus or Dur\nhams in the beef grades.\nj Norman Jeffries of Jeffries, Miss.,\ni5?5\"\nFarms of Horn Lake, Miss., will show\na string of Guernseys. These are the\nnly two Mississippi dairy herds en\nj j t m\n\nWhen it comes to good hogs, Mis-\nl\nsissippi is expected to stand toe to\n\ntoe with best the country affords.\nIn tiie Durocs, the Mississippi con\ntingent will include herds from the\nEvergreen Stock E'arm at New Site;\nEnochs Farms, Fernwood; White's\nDuroc Farm, Columbia; Pine Crest\nFarm, Charleston; Clarksdale Duroc\nE'arm, Clarksdale and L. C. Hobson\nof Houlka. W. L. Newton of New\nAlbany will show Poland Chinas and\nI the Gayoso Farm, Horn Lake, will\nshow Hampshires.\nI\nAlthough there are many herds of\nI\ni sheep m Mississippi and more and\ni\ni more of them being assembled, not\n\na sheep breeder will be represented,\nNor will there be any Mississippi\ni\ngoats exhibited.\nThe Mississippi \"red hogs\" are ex\npected to be of special interest, for\nseveral of the finest herds anywhere\nare located in the state. The Pine\nCrest, White and Enoch herds are\nknown widely for their excellence.\nIt became a question this week of\nhousing all the livestock that has\nbeen booked for the Memphis fair,\neven though bams have been doubled\nIn capacity. The same thing is true\nin every other department where en\ntries are far greater than in any oth\ner of the 12 previous Memphis ex\npositions.\nIndications point to an enormous\nattendance, the rule at all other fairs\nthroughout the country this year,\nMuch attention has been given to\namusement and entertainment feat.\nalong with the educational feat\nis\nures,\nures, and the 1920 fair will go down\nof the finest in the history of\nMr. C. W. Cunningham, who has\nen j n the office of Swift Co., has\nas one\nMemphis.\nt, e) n transferred to Sheffield, Ala.,-or\nand has departed for that place. I\nI FORD SAYS TIME\nTO CALL HALT ON\nf\nWAR GREED, ETC.\ni\nIN\nANNO! \\t IN(,\nCOMPANY'S\nRE-ESTABLISHMENT OF\n\nPRE-WAR PRICES ON\nITS PRODUCTS.\nDETROIT, Mich., Sept. 21 R,\nI tablishinent\nl' prewar prices\npi o' acts of the Ford Motor Company,\neffective immediately was announced\ntoday by Henry Ford\nThe price re\nlucli\nms range froi\napproximately 11\nper cent on motor trucks to 31 per\ncent, on smn\nautomobiles.\nIn annoi\ncompany, Mr. Ford, ii\nment said:\nn-ing the decision\n.f the\nformal state\n\"Now is a time to call\nmethods,\ning and\nhalt on vvni\nr profiteer\nwar prices, wi\nvar greed.\nIt may be nec\nessary for everybody to stand a little\nsacrifice, but it will b\nmoat profit\naide after all, because the i\nsooner wi\nget the business of the country back\nto a prewar condition, progress, pros*\nperity and coni cut ment\ne\noccupy\nthe attention of the people.\n\"For the best interests of all it i:\ntime that a real, practical effort was\nmade to bring the business of the\nis\ncountry and the life of tin\ndown to normal.\nnuntry\nInflated prices\nways retard progress. M\nThe* announcement su\nlid the price\nreductions wore made despite unfilled\norders for 140,0GB vehicles.\nThere will be no reduction in wages\nlit any of the Ford plant s, it was an\nnounced.\nn\nTWO TRIPS OCT.\nOne Will Take Hii\nAs Ear South As\nChattanooga And Other West\nTi\nKansas.\nAssociated Press\nMARION o Sent. 22\u2014It\nwas an\nnounced today that Senator llanllhg\nplans to make two campaign trips\nin October, one which will take him\nas, far South as Chattanooga and the\nother as far West\nKansas and\nOmaha.\n-o\nMILLERAND IS\nTO BE CANDIDATE\nSelected By A Joint Caucus Ah Ci\ndidate For Presidency To Suc\nceed Deschanel.\nAssociated Press\nPARIS, Sept.\n22\u2014Premier Alex\nander Milierand was chosen by a\njoint caucus of the members of the\nSenate and Chamber of Deputies as\na candidate for the presidency to suc\nceed former President Deschanel, who\nresigned because of ill health.\n\nBANDITS ROB A\nDETROIT BANK\nBranch Of First State Bank Is Rob\nbed Of Thirty Thousand\nDollars.\nDETROIT, Sept. 22\u2014Four bandits\nheld up a branch of the E'irst Nation-!\nal Bank at Mount Elliott and Mack\nAvenue today, escaping with the am\nount estimated by bank officials at\n$30,000.\nBusiness Depression\nIs Felt At Itta Bena\nITTA BENA, Miss., Sept. 22\u2014Spe- i\ncial\u2014Great business depression is be- j of\ning felt here for the past two or three I\nweeks. Merchants complain of poor\nbusiness, and some are even letting a;'\n\nclerk or two go, on account of hav\ning nothing to do. Cotton and cot\nton seed are not bringing what was\nexpected, and cotton buyers will not\nbuy. Cotton purchased under contract\nis being taken up, but free lance buy\ning is not in evidence. Business pros\npects for the fall and winter here are\ncertainly poor, unless a new and un\nexpected turn of affairs takes place.\nMr. Ed Jones was a business visit-\nhere today from his plantation\nhome at Schlater.\nDIMINISHING ON\nT]\nE IS\nTHE GULF COAST\nWarnings\nDown As Danger Is\nPassing\nAre\nTaken\nNO LIVES ARE\nBELIEVED LOST\nConsiderable Property\nI damaged Reported\nIn Places.\nAssociated Press\nWASHINGTON, Sept.. 22 The\n:en\n<*f the tropical hurricane paased\nthe inland West\nDo\nf the M ississippi\nRiver during the night and is now\niviT Northern Louisiana, the Weather\nBureau announced at 0:80 this\nmorn\nrim .storm will diminish in in\ntensity the* Ilureau says and\nore ordered taken down on the\ning.\nmgs\n(iulf ('oast.\nOwing to the interruption\nwith points\nf wire\nill the\n'oinmunientii\nGulf Coast West of this city, difficult\ntj\nms experienced i\nobtaining In\nformation from the section where tho\nturm went inland. Railway traffic\nInis been greatly delayed because of\nhigh water and destruction of the\nwire line. Great anxiety in\ned for the rice and sugar crops in St.\nMary and Terrebonne purr tabus and\nalong the Bayou Tec he, which\nbelieved to have been in the direct\npath of the storm. Only customary\ndamage which follows heavy winds\nwas reported from points on the coast\nFast of the city.\nixpress\nIII!\nCOAST ONLY SLIGHTLY\nDAMAGED.\nMOBILE, Sept. 22 The Gulf Coast\nbetween Mobile and New Orleans suf\nfered only slight damage in last\nnight's storm, according to informa\ntion received over the wires on the\nNashville-Louisville road today. No\nserious damage was reported from\nany of the coast cities.\nPROPERTY DAMAGE AT NEW\nemaiA\nNEW ORLEANS, Sept. 22\u2014Con\nsiderable property damage was done\nin New Orleans and vicinity last\nnight by high winds and rain. Dur\ning the height, of the storm the wind\nreached a maximum velocity of 48\nmiles an hour. Numbers of plate\nglass windows wore broken and signs\nblown down. Reports from the Gulf\ncoast indicate that considerable da\nmage was done to the Louisville and\nNashville road. The big bridge over\nthe Rigolets was reported destroyed\nand the bridge at Chefraenteur im\npassable.\nSTORM HITS LOUISIANA COAST.\nNEW ORLEANS, Sept. 22\u2014The\ntropical hurricane hit the Louisiana\nCoast last night .striking with full\nforce at a point close to Morgan City,\naccording to an announcement this\nmorning by Dr. I. M. Cline, District\nForecaster of the Weather Bureau\nhere.\nNO KNOWN LOSS OF LIFE.\nNEW ORLEANS, Sept. 22\u2014Pass\nengers arriving today from Morgan\nCity, near which place the weather\nbureau reports Indicated a tropical\nhurricane swept inland last night,\nstated there was no known loss of\nlife in Morgan City and ports. Ac\ncording to reports received, only\nhigh tides and moderate winds pre\nvailed. Considerable damage was\ndone to the gulf coast traction lines,\nbetween Long Beach and Pass Christ\nian, Miss.\nBELIEVE DANGER LS PAST.\nGALVESTON, Sept. 22\u2014With the\nstorm reported having passed the in\nland without striking Texas, the coast\nthis state has resumed normal act\nivities in belief that the danger is\npast,\nf Galveston and other coast cities,\nCondition MacSweeney\nIs Unchanged Today\nAssociated Press\ni DON DON, Sept. 22\u2014The condition\nj of Lor<l Ma yor MacSweeney of Cork,\nI ivho bp K\" n th f 'irty first day of his\nhunger strike in the Brixton prison\n0!bl v unchanged from yesterday,\naccording to a bulletin issued by the\nIrish Self Determination League.\nSinn Feiner Is\nShot And Killed\nAssociated Press\nDUBLIN, Sept. 22\u2014County Coun-\ncillor Lynch, prominent Sinn Feiner\nwas shot and killed in his hotel a-\npartment today, it is alleged by the\n\"black and tan\" police.","height":"19248","width":"12720"}}
